snippet.textDisplay:
I'm not talking to the Mac fans here, who can understandably get very emotional about an artist they love passing away. But Fantano has never been a fan of Mac Miller's music, and has been a pretty fierce critic of all of his albums.


So I can't help but roll my eyes when I see these fake tears of his. This is the second time I've seen Fantano do this crying bit (He did it in the Ventura review), and it's pretty cringe tbh. Dude is laying it on really thick here. I'm pretty tired of people having to hop on the bandwagon when someone passes away. If you weren't a fan, then just accept that you're not a part of the moment and move on. But some people are so desperate to keep the spotlight on them, that they are going to act like they're hurting as well just to fit in.


Mac Miller has tons of fans that are heartbroken at the loss of his life. They don't need a charlatan pretending to sympathize with them, especially one that is profiting off of this obvious playacting.


RIP to Mac Miller. But I hope he's remembered by the people who he actually had an impact on. I don't care about these clout chasing, egotistical psychopaths pretending to be touched by his music only AFTER he dies. Fantano is about to give Circles a 9 or 10 smh

This song felt and sounded nice, but didn't do too much for me, because I never followed Mac Miller very closely.

Our favorite melon man crying, and everything he had to say about the song was enlightening, but it's just not possible to brute force an instant emotional connection into me.

Then I read the comments. Just the fucking overwhelming amount of comfort and love for Anthony, coming from practically everyone. Why was THAT what got me? It hit me like hearing sympathetic words from a parent as a child, including the huge hug that follows. Whoever's reading this, yes you, please show some love to the people in your life you give a million remote control flying fucks about.

snippet.textDisplay:
I never listened to Mac Miller personally nor Arianna outside of her acting stint so while I was not emotionally invested in the artist, the track's surrealist atmosphere can be quite gripping.
Some of the lyrics aren't particularly ground-breaking but overall the song is hauntingly beautiful in portraying a tired artist reflecting on his mortality and his place within the lives of those he cares about.

A very emotional charged track with a suiting video that will soften your heart a bit and make you consider what really is beyond this life for all of us. A great way to open the year.
